Virginia, officially the Commonwealth of Virginia, [a] is a state in the [Southeastern](/Southeastern_United_States) and [Mid-Atlantic](/Mid-Atlantic_(United_States)) regions of the [United States](/United_States), situated between the [Atlantic Coast](/East_Coast_of_the_United_States) and the [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains). Its capital is [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia), and its most populous city is [Virginia Beach](/Virginia_Beach,_Virginia). The most populous subdivision is [Fairfax County](/Fairfax_County,_Virginia), part of [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia), where over a third of Virginia's 8.8 million inhabitants reside.

Eastern Virginia, characterized by the [Atlantic Plain](/Atlantic_Plain), includes the [Middle Peninsula](/Middle_Peninsula), which forms the mouth of the [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay). Central Virginia lies primarily within the [Piedmont](/Piedmont_(United_States)), a region of foothills leading to the [Blue Ridge Mountains](/Blue_Ridge_Mountains) that traverse the western and southwestern parts of the state. The fertile [Shenandoah Valley](/Shenandoah_Valley) supports the state's most productive agricultural counties, while the economy of Northern Virginia is driven by [technology companies](/Technology_company) and [U.S. federal government](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States) agencies. The [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads) area is also significant, hosting the region's primary seaport and [Naval Station Norfolk](/Naval_Station_Norfolk), the world's largest naval base.

The history of Virginia begins with [several Indigenous groups](/Native_American_tribes_in_Virginia), including the [Powhatan](/Powhatan). In 1607, the [London Company](/London_Company) established the [Colony of Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia), the first permanent [English colony](/English_overseas_possessions) in the [New World](/New_World), earning Virginia its nickname, the Old Dominion. The plantation economy, fueled by enslaved Africans and land acquired from displaced Native American tribes, grew significantly, though this growth was also accompanied by internal and external conflicts. Virginians played a pivotal role in the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution), fighting for the independence of the [Thirteen Colonies](/Thirteen_Colonies) and contributing to the establishment of the new national government. During the [American Civil War](/Virginia_in_the_American_Civil_War), Virginia's government in Richmond joined the [Confederacy](/Confederated_States_of_America). However, many northwestern counties remained loyal to the [Union](/Union_(American_Civil_War)), ultimately leading to the secession of [West Virginia](/West_Virginia) in 1863.

Following a century of near-uninterrupted Democratic rule after the [Reconstruction era](/Reconstruction_era_of_the_United_States), Virginia has seen competitive elections between both major political parties since the repeal of [racial segregation laws](/Jim_Crow_laws) in the 1960s and 1970s. The [Virginia General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly), established in July 1619, is the oldest continuously existing legislative body in [North America](/North_America). Unlike most states, Virginia's cities and counties function as approximate equals, though the state government manages most local roads. It is also unique in that its governors are prohibited from serving consecutive terms.

## History

### Earliest inhabitants

*   Main article: [Native American tribes in Virginia](/Native_American_tribes_in_Virginia)

Nomadic hunters are estimated to have arrived in Virginia around 17,000 years ago. Archaeological evidence from [Daugherty's Cave](/Daugherty%27s_Cave_and_Breeding_Site) indicates its regular use as a [rock shelter](/Rock_shelter) by 9,800 years ago. [6] During the late [Woodland period](/Woodland_period) (500–1000 CE), tribal structures began to coalesce, and agriculture, initially of corn and squash, became established. Beans and tobacco, originating from [the southwest](/Southwestern_United_States) and Mexico, arrived by the end of this period. By 1200 CE, the construction of [palisaded](/Palisade) towns had become common. The native population within the present-day boundaries of Virginia reached approximately 50,000 in the 1500s. [7] Prominent groups at this time included the [Algonquian](/Algonquian_peoples) in the [Tidewater region](/Tidewater_region_of_Virginia), who referred to their territory as [Tsenacommacah](/Tsenacommacah). The [Iroquoian](/Iroquoian_languages)-speaking [Nottoway](/Nottoway_Tribe) and [Meherrin](/Meherrin) occupied lands to the north and south, respectively, while the [Siouan](/Siouan_languages)-speaking [Tutelo](/Tutelo) were situated to the west. [8]

In response to threats from these neighboring groups to their established trade networks, approximately thirty [Virginia Algonquian](/Powhatan_language)-speaking tribes unified under Wahunsenacawh, known to the English as [Chief Powhatan](/Chief_Powhatan). [8] By 1607, Powhatan commanded over 150 settlements with a total population of around 15,000. [9] However, an estimated three-fourths of Virginia's native population succumbed to [smallpox](/Smallpox) and other [Old World diseases](/Old_World_diseases) within that century, [10] disrupting their [oral traditions](/Oral_tradition) and complicating historical research into earlier periods. [11] Furthermore, many primary sources, including those detailing the life of Powhatan's daughter, [Pocahontas](/Pocahontas), were created by Europeans, who may have harbored biases or misunderstood native social structures and customs. [5] [12]

### Colony

*   Main article: [Colony of Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia)

Several European expeditions explored the [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay) during the 16th century, including the [Spanish Jesuits](/Ajac%C3%A1n_Mission). [13] To counter [Spain's colonies in the Caribbean](/Spanish_West_Indies), Queen [Elizabeth I of England](/Elizabeth_I_of_England) supported [Walter Raleigh](/Walter_Raleigh)'s 1584 expedition to the [Atlantic coast of North America](/East_Coast_of_the_United_States). [14] [15] The name "Virginia" first appeared in Captain [Arthur Barlowe](/Arthur_Barlowe)'s expedition report and may have been suggested by Raleigh or Elizabeth I, possibly referencing her title as the "Virgin Queen" or the perceived untouched nature of the land. Alternatively, it could derive from an [Algonquin](/Algonquin_language) phrase, "Wingandacoa" or "Windgancon," or the name of a leader, [Wingina](/Wingina), as heard by the expedition. [16] [17] Initially, the name applied to the entire coastal region from [South Carolina](/South_Carolina) in the south to [Maine](/Maine) in the north, as well as the island of [Bermuda](/Bermuda). [18] Although [Raleigh's colony](/Roanoke_Colony) failed, the potential financial and strategic advantages continued to attract English policymakers. In 1606, [King James I](/James_I_of_England) granted a [charter for a new colony](/First_Virginia_Charter) to the [Virginia Company of London](/London_Company). This group financed an expedition led by [Christopher Newport](/Christopher_Newport), which established the settlement of [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia) in 1607. [19]

Despite the arrival of more settlers, many were ill-equipped to handle the dangers of the new settlement. As the colony's president, [John Smith](/John_Smith_(explorer)) secured food supplies from nearby tribes. However, after his departure in 1609, this trade ceased, initiating a period of [mass starvation in the colony](/Starving_Time_(Jamestown)) and a series of [ambush-style killings](/Anglo-Powhatan_Wars) between colonists and natives under [Chief Powhatan](/Powhatan_(Native_American_leader)) and [his brother](/Opechancanough). [20] By the end of the colony's first fourteen years, over eighty percent of the approximately eight thousand settlers transported there had perished. [21] The increasing [demand for exported tobacco](/Tobacco_in_the_American_Colonies), however, necessitated a greater labor force. [22] Beginning in 1618, the [headright](/Headright) system was implemented to address this, granting colonists tracts of land for their efforts in attracting [indentured servants](/Indentured_servant). [23] Enslaved Africans were first introduced to Virginia in 1619. [First_Africans_in_Virginia] While other Africans arrived as indentured servants and could gain freedom after four to seven years, the legal foundation for [lifelong slavery](/History_of_slavery_in_Virginia) was established through court cases involving individuals like [John Punch](/John_Punch_(slave)) in 1640 and [John Casor](/John_Casor) in 1655. [24] Laws enacted in Jamestown in 1661 defined slavery as [race-based](/Race_(human_categorization)), in 1662 as [inherited maternally](/Partus_sequitur_ventrem), and in 1669 as punishable by death. [25]

In 1699, following a fire that destroyed the statehouse in [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia), the capital of the [Colony of Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia) was relocated to [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia), where the [College of William & Mary](/College_of_William_%26_Mary) had been founded six years prior. [26]

From the colony's inception, residents advocated for greater local control. By 1619, certain male colonists began electing representatives to an assembly, later known as the [House of Burgesses](/House_of_Burgesses), which engaged in negotiations with the [governing council](/Virginia_Governor%27s_Council) appointed by the London Company. [27] Dissatisfied with this arrangement, the monarchy revoked the company's charter in 1624, assuming direct control by appointing governors and Council members. In 1635, colonists arrested a governor who had defied the assembly, [John Harvey (Virginia governor)](/John_Harvey_(Virginia_governor)), and forcibly sent him back to England. [28] [William Berkeley](/William_Berkeley_(governor)) was appointed governor in 1642, coinciding with a period of increased colonial autonomy facilitated by the turmoil of the [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War) and [Interregnum](/British_Interregnum). [29] As a royalist supporter, Berkeley welcomed numerous [Cavaliers](/Virginia_Cavaliers_(historical)) fleeing England. He surrendered to [Parliamentarians](/Roundhead) in 1652. Upon his reappointment as governor after the 1660 [Restoration](/Stuart_Restoration), Berkeley suppressed assembly elections and exacerbated class divisions by disenfranchising and restricting the movement of indentured servants, who constituted approximately eighty percent of the workforce. [30] On the colony's frontier, tribes such as the [Tutelo](/Tutelo) and [Doeg](/Doeg_people) faced pressure from [Seneca](/Seneca_people) raiders advancing from the north, leading to increased conflict with colonists. In 1676, a rebellion led by [Nathaniel Bacon](/Nathaniel_Bacon_(Virginia_colonist)), fueled by resentment over Berkeley's refusal to retaliate against the tribes, resulted in the burning of Jamestown. [31]

[Bacon's Rebellion](/Bacon%27s_Rebellion) led to the enactment of [Bacon's Laws](/Bacon%27s_Laws), which restored certain colonial rights and sanctioned both attacks on native tribes and the enslavement of their people. [32] [33] The [Treaty of 1677](/Treaty_of_1677) further diminished the autonomy of the signatory tribes, facilitating the colony's subsequent land acquisition. [34] [35] In the 1700s, colonists expanded westward into territories claimed by the Seneca and the broader [Iroquois Nation](/Iroquois). In 1748, the [Ohio Company](/Ohio_Company), a consortium of wealthy speculators backed by the British monarchy, was formed to establish English settlements and trade in the [Ohio Country], west of the [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains). [36] France, asserting its claim to this region as part of [New France](/New_France), viewed this expansion as a provocation, igniting the [French and Indian War](/French_and_Indian_War) in 1754, which involved England, France, the Iroquois, and allied tribes on both sides. The [Virginia Regiment], a militia comprised of soldiers from several British colonies, was led by Major [George Washington](/George_Washington), himself an investor in the Ohio Company. [37]

### Statehood

*   See also: [Virginia in the American Revolution](/Virginia_in_the_American_Revolution)
*   In 1765, [Patrick Henry](/Patrick_Henry) led a [protest](/Virginia_Resolves) against the unpopular [Stamp Act](/Stamp_Act_1765) in the [House of Burgesses](/House_of_Burgesses), an event later immortalized in this portrait by [Peter F. Rothermel](/Peter_F._Rothermel).

In the decade following the [French and Indian War](/French_and_Indian_War), the [British Parliament](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) enacted new taxes that were met with widespread opposition in the colonies. Within the [House of Burgesses](/House_of_Burgesses), figures such as [Patrick Henry](/Patrick_Henry) and [Richard Henry Lee](/Richard_Henry_Lee) emerged as leaders in the protest against [taxation without representation](/No_taxation_without_representation). [38] In 1773, Virginians began coordinating their actions with other colonies through [committees of correspondence](/Committee_of_correspondence), and the following year, they dispatched delegates to the [Continental Congress](/Continental_Congress). [39] Following the dissolution of the House of Burgesses in 1774 by [the royal governor](/John_Murray,_4th_Earl_of_Dunmore), Virginia's revolutionary leaders continued to govern through the [Virginia Conventions](/Virginia_Conventions). On May 15, 1776, the Convention declared Virginia's independence and adopted [George Mason](/George_Mason)'s [Virginia Declaration of Rights](/Virginia_Declaration_of_Rights), which was subsequently incorporated into a new constitution designating Virginia as a [commonwealth](/Commonwealth). [40] [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson), another prominent Virginian, drew upon Mason's work in drafting the national [Declaration of Independence](/United_States_Declaration_of_Independence). [41]

Following the commencement of the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War), [George Washington](/George_Washington) was appointed by the [Second Continental Congress](/Second_Continental_Congress) in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia) to lead the [Continental Army](/Continental_Army). Many [Virginians joined the army](/Virginia_Line) and participated in revolutionary militias. Virginia was the first colony to ratify the [Articles of Confederation](/Articles_of_Confederation) in December 1777. [42] In April 1780, Governor Thomas Jefferson urged the relocation of the capital to [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia), citing concerns about Williamsburg's coastal vulnerability to British attack. [43] British forces under [Benedict Arnold](/Benedict_Arnold) captured [Portsmouth](/Portsmouth,_Virginia) in December 1780 and subsequently raided [Richmond](/Raid_on_Richmond) the following month. [44] By early 1781, the British army had deployed over seven thousand soldiers and twenty-five warships in Virginia. However, indecisiveness among British command, including [General Charles Cornwallis](/Charles_Cornwallis,_1st_Marquess_Cornwallis), coupled with the strategic maneuvers of approximately three thousand soldiers under the [Marquis de Lafayette](/Gilbert_du_Motier,_Marquis_de_Lafayette) and the presence of twenty-nine allied French warships, effectively confined the British to a marshy area of the [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) by September. A decisive force of around sixteen thousand soldiers, led by George Washington and [Comte de Rochambeau](/Comte_de_Rochambeau), converged on the location, culminating in the defeat of Cornwallis during the [siege of Yorktown](/Siege_of_Yorktown). [45] Cornwallis's surrender on October 19, 1781, precipitated [peace negotiations in Paris](/Peace_of_Paris_(1783)) and secured the independence of the colonies. [46]

Virginians played a significant role in the formulation of the [United States Constitution](/United_States_Constitution). [James Madison](/James_Madison) authored the [Virginia Plan](/Virginia_Plan) in 1787 and the [Bill of Rights](/United_States_Bill_of_Rights) in 1789. [41] Virginia ratified the Constitution on June 25, 1788. The [three-fifths compromise](/Three-fifths_compromise) ensured that Virginia, with its substantial enslaved population, initially held the largest delegation in the [House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives). This, combined with the [Virginia dynasty](/Virginia_dynasty) of presidents, cemented the Commonwealth's national importance. Virginia is often referred to as the "Mother of States" due to its role in the formation of new states, such as [Kentucky](/Kentucky), and for the significant number of [American pioneers](/American_pioneer) born within its borders. [47]

### Civil War

*   Main article: [Virginia in the American Civil War](/Virginia_in_the_American_Civil_War)
*   Eyre Crowe's 1853 portrait, *Slaves Waiting for Sale: Richmond, Virginia*, depicted the city's slave markets where thousands were sold annually. [48]

Between 1790 and 1860, the enslaved population in Virginia increased from approximately 290,000 to over 490,000, constituting roughly one-third of the state's population. The number of slave owners also rose to over 50,000, with both figures being the highest in the U.S. [49] [50] The expansion of [Southern cotton production](/Cotton_Belt), facilitated by [cotton gins](/Cotton_gin) for harvesting [upland cotton](/Gossypium_hirsutum), intensified the demand for labor. Concurrently, [new federal laws](/Act_Prohibiting_Importation_of_Slaves) prohibited the international importation of slaves. Decades of [monoculture](/Monoculture) tobacco farming had also diminished Virginia's [agricultural productivity](/Agricultural_productivity). [51] Virginia plantations increasingly relied on the [export of slaves](/Slave_trade_in_the_United_States), a practice that fractured numerous families and transformed the [breeding of slaves](/Slave_breeding_in_the_United_States), often through sexual violence, into a lucrative enterprise. [52] [53] Enslaved individuals in the [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia) area were also subjected to forced labor in industrial sectors, including mining and shipbuilding. [54] Resistance to slavery grew, marked by failed slave uprisings led by [Gabriel Prosser](/Gabriel_Prosser) in 1800, [George Boxley](/George_Boxley) in 1815, and [Nat Turner](/Nat_Turner) in 1831. In response to fears of further uprisings, Virginia's government encouraged the migration of free Black individuals to [Liberia](/Liberia) during the 1830s. [51]

On October 16, 1859, abolitionist [John Brown](/John_Brown_(abolitionist)) led a [raid on Harpers Ferry, Virginia](/John_Brown%27s_Raid_on_Harpers_Ferry) with the objective of inciting a widespread slave revolt across the Southern states. The polarized national reaction to his capture, trial, and execution in December of that year served as a critical turning point for many who believed that slavery would ultimately be abolished through force. [55] The election of [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) in 1860 further solidified the conviction among many Southern proponents of slavery that his opposition to its expansion foreshadowed its eventual demise nationwide. The [seizure of Fort Sumter](/Battle_of_Fort_Sumter) by [Confederate](/Confederate_States_of_America) forces on April 14, 1861, prompted Lincoln to [call for the federalization of 75,000 militiamen](/Proclamation_80). [56]

The [Confederacy](/Confederate_States_of_America) established [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia) as its capital from May 1861 until April 1865, when the city was abandoned and its [downtown](/Shockoe_Slip) was set ablaze.

The [Virginia Secession Convention of 1861](/Virginia_Secession_Convention_of_1861) voted on April 17 to [secede](/Ordinance_of_Secession), contingent upon approval in a referendum the following month. The convention resolved to join the Confederacy, which subsequently designated [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia) as its capital on May 20. [47] During the May 23 referendum, armed pro-Confederate groups obstructed the casting and tallying of votes from areas opposing secession. Representatives from 27 of these northwestern counties convened the [Wheeling Convention](/Wheeling_Convention), establishing a government loyal to the [Union](/Union_(Civil_War)) and initiating the separation of [West Virginia](/West_Virginia) as a new state. [57]

The first engagement between Union and Confederate armies occurred on July 21, 1861, at the [Battle of Bull Run](/First_Battle_of_Bull_Run) near [Manassas, Virginia](/Manassas,_Virginia), resulting in a decisive Confederate victory. Union General [George B. McClellan](/George_B._McClellan) organized the [Army of the Potomac](/Army_of_the_Potomac), which landed on the [Virginia Peninsula](/Peninsula_campaign) in March 1862 and advanced to the outskirts of Richmond by June. Following the wounding of Confederate General [Joseph E. Johnston](/Joseph_E._Johnston) in fighting near the city, command of his [Army of Northern Virginia](/Army_of_Northern_Virginia) was transferred to [Robert E. Lee](/Robert_E._Lee). Over the subsequent month, Lee repelled the Union army in the [Seven Days Battles](/Seven_Days_Battles) and subsequently led [the first of several invasions](/Maryland_campaign) into Union territory beginning in September. For the ensuing three years of the war, Virginia hosted more battles than any other state, including engagements at [Fredericksburg](/Battle_of_Fredericksburg), [Chancellorsville](/Battle_of_Chancellorsville), [Spotsylvania](/Battle_of_Spotsylvania_Court_House), and the concluding [Battle of Appomattox Court House](/Battle_of_Appomattox_Court_House), where Lee surrendered on April 9, 1865. [58]

### Reconstruction and segregation

The [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads) Port of Embarkation at Newport News served as the second-largest U.S. port of embarkation during [World War I](/World_War_I), processing nearly 800,000 American soldiers. [59]

Virginia was formally readmitted to the United States in 1870, largely due to the efforts of the [Committee of Nine](/Committee_of_Nine). [60] During the post-war [Reconstruction era](/Reconstruction_era_of_the_United_States), African Americans established cohesive communities, particularly around [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia), [Danville](/Danville,_Virginia), and the [Tidewater region](/Tidewater_(region)), and gained greater participation in Virginia society. Many achieved some level of land ownership during the 1870s. [61] [62] Virginia adopted a [constitution in 1868](/Virginia_Constitutional_Convention_of_1868) that guaranteed political and civil rights, including [voting rights](/Voting_rights_in_the_United_States), and established free public education. [63] However, the extensive destruction of railroad lines and other infrastructure during the Civil War left the Commonwealth heavily indebted. In the late 1870s, funds allocated for public schools were redirected to satisfy bondholder obligations. The [Readjuster Party](/Readjuster_Party) emerged in 1877, gaining legislative control in 1879 by uniting Black and white Virginians against debt repayment policies and the influence of perceived [plantation elites](/Planter_class). [64]

The Readjusters prioritized educational development, supporting institutions like [Virginia Tech](/Virginia_Tech) and [Virginia State](/Virginia_State_University), and successfully compelled [West Virginia](/West_Virginia) to assume a share of the pre-war debt. [65] However, internal divisions arose in 1883 over a proposed repeal of [anti-miscegenation laws](/Anti-miscegenation_laws). Shortly before that year's elections, a [riot in Danville](/Danville_Massacre), involving armed police, resulted in the deaths of four Black men and one white man. [66] These events fueled a concerted effort by white supremacists to seize political power through [voter suppression](/Voter_suppression_in_the_United_States). Segregationists within the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_of_Virginia) secured legislative control that year and maintained it for decades, thereby establishing the [Solid South](/Solid_South). [67] They implemented [Jim Crow laws](/Jim_Crow_laws) that enforced a system of [racial segregation in the United States](/Racial_segregation_in_the_United_States). In 1902, the [state constitution](/Constitution_of_Virginia) was revised to include a [poll tax](/Poll_tax_(United_States)) and other restrictive voter registration measures, effectively [disenfranchising](/Disfranchisement_after_the_Reconstruction_era) the majority of African Americans and a significant number of impoverished white citizens. [68]

Meanwhile, new economic forces spurred industrialization across the Commonwealth. Virginian [James Albert Bonsack](/James_Albert_Bonsack) patented a cigarette rolling machine in 1880, leading to large-scale production centered in Richmond. In 1886, railroad magnate [Collis Potter Huntington](/Collis_Potter_Huntington) founded [Newport News Shipbuilding](/Newport_News_Shipbuilding), which constructed 38 warships for the [U.S. Navy](/U.S._Navy) between 1907 and 1923. [69] During [World War I](/World_War_I), German submarines targeted ships near the port, [70] which served as a critical hub for transporting soldiers and supplies. [59] Following the war, a homecoming parade honoring African-American troops was attacked by city police in July 1919 as part of a resurgence of white supremacy known as [Red Summer](/Red_Summer). [71] The shipyard continued its role in building warships during [World War II](/World_War_II), quadrupling its pre-war workforce to 70,000 by 1943. The [Radford Arsenal](/Radford_Army_Ammunition_Plant) near [Blacksburg](/Blacksburg,_Virginia) employed 22,000 workers producing explosives, [72] while the [Torpedo Factory](/Torpedo_Factory_Art_Center) in [Alexandria](/Alexandria,_Virginia) employed over 5,050. [73]

### Civil rights to present

Protests in 2020 focused on [Confederate monuments in the state](/List_of_Confederate_monuments_and_memorials_in_Virginia).

High school student [Barbara Rose Johns](/Barbara_Rose_Johns) initiated a strike in 1951 at her underfunded and segregated school in [Prince Edward County](/Prince_Edward_County,_Virginia). The ensuing protests led [Spottswood Robinson](/Spottswood_William_Robinson_III) and [Oliver Hill](/Oliver_Hill_(attorney)) to file a [lawsuit against the county](/Davis_v._County_School_Board_of_Prince_Edward_County). Their case was consolidated with [Brown v. Board of Education](/Brown_v._Board_of_Education) before the Supreme Court, which in 1954 rejected the doctrine of "[separate but equal](/Separate_but_equal)". The segregationist establishment, spearheaded by Senator [Harry F. Byrd](/Harry_F._Byrd) and his [Byrd Organization](/Byrd_Organization), responded with a strategy known as "[massive resistance](/Massive_resistance)". In 1956, the General Assembly enacted a series of laws, the [Stanley Plan](/Stanley_Plan), that terminated funding for local schools integrating their student bodies, leading to the closure of some. Court rulings declared this strategy unconstitutional, and on February 2, 1959, Black students successfully integrated schools in [Arlington](/Arlington_County,_Virginia) and [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia), becoming known as the [Norfolk 17](/Norfolk_17). [74] Rather than comply with integration orders, county leaders in Prince Edward closed their school system in June 1959. After further litigation reached the Supreme Court in [Griffin v. County School Board of Prince Edward County](/Griffin_v._County_School_Board_of_Prince_Edward_County), the court mandated the reopening and integration of the county's schools, which finally occurred in September 1964. [75] [76]

Federal legislation, including the [Civil Rights Act](/Civil_Rights_Act_of_1964) (1964) and the [Voting Rights Act](/Voting_Rights_Act_of_1965), along with subsequent enforcement by the [Justice Department](/United_States_Department_of_Justice), played a crucial role in dismantling racial segregation in Virginia and overturning [Jim Crow laws](/Jim_Crow_laws). [77] In 1967, the Supreme Court decision in [Loving v. Virginia](/Loving_v._Virginia) invalidated the state's prohibition on [interracial marriage](/Interracial_marriage_in_the_United_States). In 1968, Governor [Mills Godwin](/Mills_Godwin) convened a commission tasked with revising the state constitution. The new constitution, which outlawed discrimination and removed provisions conflicting with federal law, was approved by referendum and took effect in 1971. [78] In 1989, [Douglas Wilder](/Douglas_Wilder) made history as the first African American elected governor in the United States. In 1992, [Bobby Scott](/Bobby_Scott_(politician)) became Virginia's first Black congressman since 1888. [79] [80]

The expansion of federal government offices into the suburbs of Northern Virginia during the [Cold War](/Cold_War) significantly boosted the region's population and economic growth. [81] The [Central Intelligence Agency](/Central_Intelligence_Agency), outgrowing its facilities in [Foggy Bottom](/Foggy_Bottom), relocated to [Langley](/Langley,_Virginia) in 1961, partly in response to a [National Security Council](/United_States_National_Security_Council) directive to move the agency outside of Washington, D.C. [82] [The Pentagon](/The_Pentagon), constructed in [Arlington](/Arlington_County,_Virginia) during [World War II](/World_War_II) to serve as the headquarters for the Department of Defense, was struck by a hijacked aircraft during the [September 11, 2001 attacks](/September_11,_2001_attacks). [83] Mass shootings at [Virginia Tech in 2007](/Virginia_Tech_shooting) and in [Virginia Beach in 2019](/2019_Virginia_Beach_shooting) prompted the passage of gun control measures in 2020. [84] Concerns regarding racial injustice and the prominent display of [Confederate monuments in Virginia](/List_of_Confederate_monuments_and_memorials_in_Virginia) have also catalyzed substantial demonstrations. Notably, in August 2017, a white supremacist drove his vehicle into protesters, resulting in one fatality. In June 2020, protests associated with the broader [Black Lives Matter](/Black_Lives_Matter) movement led to the [removal of Confederate statues](/Removal_of_Confederate_monuments_and_memorials). [85]

## Geography

*   Main article: [Environment of Virginia](/Environment_of_Virginia)
*   Virginia's topography is shaped by the [Blue Ridge Mountains](/Blue_Ridge_Mountains), the [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay) and its watershed, and the [parallel 36°30′ north](/Parallel_36%C2%B030%E2%80%B2_north).

Virginia is situated in the [Mid-Atlantic](/Mid-Atlantic_(United_States)) and [Southeastern](/Southeastern_United_States) regions of the United States. [86] [87] With a total area of 42,774.2 square miles (110,784.7 km 2 ), including 3,180.13 square miles (8,236.5 km 2 ) of water, Virginia ranks as the 35th-[largest state](/List_of_U.S._states_by_area) by area. [88] It shares borders with [Maryland](/Maryland) and [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.) to the northeast; the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) to the east; [North Carolina](/North_Carolina) to the south; [Tennessee](/Tennessee) to the southwest; [Kentucky](/Kentucky) to the west; and [West Virginia](/West_Virginia) to the northwest. The boundary between Virginia and Maryland, defined by the low-water mark of the south shore of the [Potomac River](/Potomac_River), has historically been a point of contention regarding [water rights](/Water_right). [89]

Virginia's southern border was established in 1665 as [36°30' north latitude](/Parallel_36%C2%B030%E2%80%B2_north). [Royal_Colonial_Boundary_of_1665] However, surveyors marking the border with North Carolina in the 18th century began approximately 3.5 miles (5.6 km) north of this line and deviated further westward, extending an additional 3.5 miles by [the border's westernmost point](/North_Carolina%E2%80%93Tennessee%E2%80%93Virginia_Corners). [90] Following Tennessee's admission to the U.S. in 1796, new surveys in 1802 and 1803 redefined its border with Virginia as a line extending from the summit of [White Top Mountain](/White_Top_Mountain) to the peak of [Tri-State Peak](/Tri-State_Peak) in the [Cumberland Mountains](/Cumberland_Mountains). Nevertheless, discrepancies in this border were identified during its re-marking in 1856, prompting the Virginia General Assembly to propose a new surveying commission in 1871. Representatives from Tennessee favored maintaining the less precise 1803 boundary, and in 1893, the [U.S. Supreme Court](/U.S._Supreme_Court) ruled in favor of Tennessee in its dispute with Virginia. [91] [92] A notable consequence of these boundary issues is the division of the city of [Bristol](/Bristol,_Virginia) between the two states. [93]

### Geology and terrain

*   Main article: [Geology of Virginia](/Geology_of_Virginia)
*   [Great Falls](/Great_Falls_(Potomac_River)), situated on the [fall line](/Atlantic_Seaboard_Fall_Line) of the [Potomac River](/Potomac_River), features rocks dating to the late [Precambrian](/Precambrian). [94]

The [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay) divides the contiguous portion of the Commonwealth from the two-county peninsula known as Virginia's [Eastern Shore](/Eastern_Shore_of_Virginia). The bay itself was formed from the [drowned river valley](/Ria) of the ancient [Susquehanna River](/Susquehanna_River). [95] Numerous [Virginia's rivers](/List_of_rivers_of_Virginia), including the [Potomac](/Potomac_River), [Rappahannock](/Rappahannock_River), [York](/York_River_(Virginia)), and [James](/James_River), flow into the Chesapeake Bay. These rivers create three peninsulas, traditionally referred to as "necks," named [Northern Neck](/Northern_Neck), [Middle Peninsula](/Middle_Peninsula), and the [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) from north to south. [96] [Sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise) has contributed to the erosion of Virginia's islands, including [Tangier Island](/Tangier,_Virginia) in the bay and [Chincoteague](/Chincoteague,_Virginia), one of [23 barrier islands](/Virginia_Barrier_Islands) along the Atlantic coast. [97] [98]

The [Tidewater](/Tidewater_(geographic_term)) region is a [coastal plain](/Atlantic_coastal_plain) situated between the Atlantic coastline and the [fall line](/Atlantic_Seaboard_fall_line). This region encompasses the Eastern Shore and the major [estuaries](/Estuary) of the Chesapeake Bay. East of the mountains lies the Piedmont, a region characterized by [foothills](/Foothills) formed from [sedimentary](/Sedimentary_rock) and [igneous rock](/Igneous_rock) deposits. [99] This area, known for its heavy clay soil, includes the [Southwest Mountains](/Southwest_Mountains) surrounding [Charlottesville](/Charlottesville,_Virginia). [100] The [Blue Ridge Mountains](/Blue_Ridge_Mountains), a [physiographic province](/Physiographic_regions_of_the_world) of the [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains), contain the Commonwealth's highest elevations, with [Mount Rogers](/Mount_Rogers_(Virginia)) standing as the tallest peak at 5,729 feet (1,746 m). [2] West of the Blue Ridge lies the [Ridge-and-Valley region](/Ridge-and-Valley_Appalachians), characterized by [carbonate rock](/Carbonate_rock). This region includes the [Massanutten Mountain](/Massanutten_Mountain) ridge and the [Great Appalachian Valley](/Great_Appalachian_Valley), known in Virginia as the [Shenandoah Valley](/Shenandoah_Valley), named after the [river of the same name](/Shenandoah_River) that flows through it. [101] The southwesternmost corner of Virginia is occupied by the [Cumberland Plateau](/Cumberland_Plateau) and [Cumberland Mountains](/Cumberland_Mountains), situated south of the [Allegheny Plateau](/Allegheny_Plateau). Rivers in this region flow northwestward into the [Ohio River](/Ohio_River) basin. [102]

[Virginia's seismic zones](/Virginia_seismic_zones) have historically exhibited limited regular [earthquake](/Earthquake) activity, with magnitudes rarely exceeding 4.5 on the [Richter scale](/Richter_magnitude_scale). The Commonwealth experienced its largest earthquake in at least a century, registering a magnitude of 5.8, which struck central Virginia on August 23, 2011. [2011_Virginia_earthquake] Approximately 35 million years ago, a [bolide](/Bolide) impacted the area now known as eastern Virginia. The resulting [Chesapeake Bay impact crater](/Chesapeake_Bay_impact_crater) is theorized to be a contributing factor to the region's seismic activity and [subsidence](/Subsidence). [104] A meteor impact is also hypothesized as the origin of [Lake Drummond](/Lake_Drummond), the larger of the two natural [lakes in the state](/List_of_lakes_of_Virginia). [105]

The Commonwealth's carbonate rock geology hosts over 4,000 [limestone caves](/Limestone_cave), ten of which are accessible to tourists, including the popular [Luray Caverns](/Luray_Caverns) and [Skyline Caverns](/Skyline_Caverns). [106] Virginia's iconic [Natural Bridge](/Natural_Bridge_(Virginia)) is the remnant roof of a collapsed limestone cave. [107] [Coal mining](/Coal_mining_in_the_United_States) is conducted in the state's three mountainous regions. [108] In 2020, Virginia produced over 72 million tons of non-fuel resources, such as [slate](/Slate), [kyanite](/Kyanite), sand, and gravel. [109] The largest known [uranium](/Uranium) deposits in the U.S. are located beneath [Coles Hill, Virginia](/Coles_Hill_uranium_deposit). Despite [legal challenges reaching the U.S. Supreme Court twice](/Virginia_Uranium,_Inc._v._Warren), the state has maintained a ban on uranium mining since 1982 due to environmental and public health concerns. [110]

### Climate

*   Main article: [Climate of Virginia](/Climate_of_Virginia)
*   See also: [Climate change in Virginia](/Climate_change_in_Virginia)

Virginia experiences a [humid subtropical climate](/Humid_subtropical_climate) that transitions to a [humid continental](/Humid_continental_climate) climate west of the [Blue Ridge Mountains](/Blue_Ridge_Mountains). [111] Seasonal temperature variations range from average lows of 25 °F (−4 °C) in January to average highs of 86 °F (30 °C) in July. [112] The Atlantic Ocean and the [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream) exert a significant influence on the climate of eastern and southeastern coastal areas, resulting in warmer yet more stable conditions. The majority of Virginia's recorded temperature and precipitation extremes have occurred in the Blue Ridge Mountains and adjacent western regions. [113] Virginia receives an average annual precipitation of 43.47 inches (110 cm), [112] with the [Shenandoah Valley](/Shenandoah_Valley) being the state's driest region. [113]

Virginia experiences approximately 35–45 days with thunderstorms annually, with storms typically occurring in the late afternoon and early evening between April and September. [114] These months also represent the peak season for [tornadoes](/Tornado), [115] with twelve recorded instances in the Commonwealth in 2024. [116] [Hurricanes](/List_of_Virginia_hurricanes) and tropical storms can affect the state from August through October. The deadliest natural disaster in Virginia's history was [Hurricane Camille](/Hurricane_Camille) in 1969, which caused over 150 fatalities, primarily in the inland county of [Nelson County, Virginia](/Nelson_County,_Virginia). [113] [117] Between December and March, [cold-air damming](/Cold-air_damming) events, caused by the Appalachian Mountains, can lead to substantial snowfall across the state. An example is the [January 2016 blizzard](/January_2016_United_States_blizzard), which produced the state's highest recorded one-day snowfall of 36.6 inches (93 cm) near [Bluemont](/Bluemont,_Virginia). [118] [119] On average, Virginia cities receive between 5.8–12.3 inches (15–31 cm) of snow annually. However, recent winters have experienced below-average snowfall, with much of Virginia recording no measurable snow during the 2022–2023 winter season. [120] [121]

[Climate change in Virginia](/Climate_change_in_Virginia) is contributing to rising temperatures throughout the year and an increase in heavy rainfall and flooding events. [122] [Urban heat islands](/Urban_heat_island) are prevalent in many Virginia cities and suburbs, particularly in neighborhoods historically affected by [redlining](/Redlining). [123] [124] Air quality in Virginia has shown statistical improvement since 1998. [125] The closure and conversion of [coal power plants](/Coal_power_plant) in Virginia and the Ohio Valley region have helped reduce the concentration of [particulate matter](/Particulate_pollution) in Virginia's air by half. [126] [127] Current energy policies aim to source 30% of the Commonwealth's electricity from renewable sources by 2030 and achieve 100% carbon-free electricity by 2050. [128]

### Ecosystem

*   See also: [List of endangered species in Virginia](/List_of_endangered_species_in_Virginia)
*   Up to 7,000 [white-tailed deer](/White-tailed_deer), also known as Virginia deer, inhabit [Shenandoah National Park](/Shenandoah_National_Park). [129]

As of 2021, forests cover 62% of Virginia's land area. [130] Of this forested land, 80% consists of [hardwood](/Hardwood) forests, indicating a prevalence of [deciduous](/Deciduous) and [broad-leaved](/Broad-leaved_tree) trees. The remaining 20% is pine forest, with [loblolly](/Pinus_taeda) and [shortleaf pine](/Pinus_echinata) dominating much of central and eastern Virginia. [130] In the western and mountainous regions of the Commonwealth, oak and hickory are the most common tree species, while lower elevations are more likely to feature small but dense stands of hemlocks and abundant mosses. [113] [Spongy moth infestations](/Gypsy_moths_in_the_United_States) affecting oak trees and the devastating impact of [chestnut blight](/Chestnut_blight) have led to a decline in the populations of these species, creating opportunities for hickory and the invasive [tree of heaven](/Ailanthus_altissima). [131] [113] In the lowland Tidewater and [Piedmont](/Piedmont_(United_States)) regions, yellow pines are prevalent, complemented by bald cypress wetland forests in the Great Dismal and Nottoway swamps. [130] Other significant tree species include red spruce, [Atlantic white cedar](/Chamaecyparis_thyoides), [tulip-poplar](/Liriodendron_tulipifera), and the [flowering dogwood](/Cornus_florida), which is designated as the [state tree and flower](/List_of_U.S._state_and_territory_trees). [132] Common plant species also include [milkweed](/Asclepias), dandelions, daisies, ferns, and [Virginia creeper](/Parthenocissus_quinquefolia), the latter of which is featured on the [state flag](/Flag_of_Virginia). [133] The [Thompson Wildlife Area](/G._Richard_Thompson_Wildlife_Management_Area) in [Fauquier County, Virginia](/Fauquier_County,_Virginia) is recognized for hosting one of the largest populations of [trillium wildflowers](/Trillium_grandiflorum) in North America. [113]

Virginia is home to 75 mammal species, including the [white-tailed deer](/White-tailed_deer). Their population has rebounded significantly, increasing from an estimated low of 25,000 in the 1930s to over one million by the 2010s. [134] [135] Native [carnivorans](/Carnivora) found in Virginia include [black bears](/American_black_bear), with an estimated population of five to six thousand statewide, [136] as well as [bobcats](/Bobcat), [coyotes](/Coyote), both [gray](/Gray_fox) and [red foxes](/Red_fox), [raccoons](/Raccoon), [weasels](/Weasel), and [skunks](/Skunk). Rodent species include [groundhogs](/Groundhog), [nutria](/Nutria), [beavers](/Beaver), [gray squirrels](/Eastern_gray_squirrel) and [fox squirrels](/Fox_squirrel), chipmunks, and [Allegheny woodrats](/Allegheny_woodrat). The seventeen bat species found in the state include brown bats and the [Virginia big-eared bat](/Virginia_big-eared_bat), which is designated as the [state mammal](/List_of_U.S._state_mammals). [137] [135] The [Virginia opossum](/Virginia_opossum) is the sole [marsupial](/Marsupial) native to both the United States and Canada. [138] The native [Appalachian cottontail](/Appalachian_cottontail) was recognized as a distinct rabbit species in 1992, one of three rabbit species found in the state. [139] Virginia's coastal waters host various whale, dolphin, and porpoise species, with [bottlenose dolphins](/Bottlenose_dolphins) being the most frequently observed [aquatic mammals](/Aquatic_mammal). [135]

[Osprey](/Osprey) nesting platforms at [False Cape State Park](/False_Cape_State_Park) were designed to encourage their return to the area.

Virginia's avifauna comprises 422 documented species, of which 359 are regularly observed, and 214 have been recorded breeding in the state. The remaining species are primarily [winter residents or transients](/Bird_migration). [140] [Water birds](/Water_birds) found in Virginia include sandpipers, wood ducks, and the [Virginia rail](/Virginia_rail). Common inland species consist of warblers, woodpeckers, and cardinals, the latter being the [state bird](/List_of_U.S._state_birds). Birds of prey include osprey, [broad-winged hawks](/Broad-winged_hawk), and [barred owls](/Barred_owl). There are no [endemic](/Endemic_species) bird species in Virginia. [140] [Audubon](/National_Audubon_Society) designates 21 [Important Bird Areas](/Important_Bird_Area) within the state. [142] [Peregrine falcons](/Peregrine_falcon), whose populations experienced a significant decline due to [DDT](/DDT) poisoning in the mid-20th century, are the subject of conservation initiatives in the state, including a reintroduction program in [Shenandoah National Park](/Shenandoah_National_Park). [143]

Virginia's freshwater fish diversity includes 226 species from 25 families, attributed to the region's varied climate, topography, interconnected river systems, and absence of [Pleistocene glaciers](/Pleistocene_glaciation). Common species found in the [Cumberland Plateau](/Cumberland_Plateau) and higher-elevation areas include the [Eastern blacknose dace](/Eastern_blacknose_dace), [sculpin](/Sculpin), [smallmouth bass](/Smallmouth_bass), [redhorse sucker](/Redhorse_sucker), [Kanawha darter](/Kanawha_darter), and [brook trout](/Brook_trout), the designated [state fish](/List_of_U.S._state_fish). At lower elevations in the Piedmont, species such as the [stripeback darter](/Stripeback_darter) and [Roanoke bass](/Roanoke_bass) become more common, as do [swampfish](/Swampfish), [bluespotted sunfish](/Bluespotted_sunfish), and [pirate perch](/Pirate_perch) in the [Tidewater](/Tidewater_(region)) area. [144] The [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay) supports populations of clams, oysters, and 350 species of [saltwater](/Saltwater_fish) and [estuarine fish](/Coastal_fish). Among these are the bay's most abundant finfish, the [Bay anchovy](/Bay_anchovy), and the invasive [blue catfish](/Blue_catfish). [145] [146] As of 2025, an estimated 238 million [Chesapeake blue crabs](/Callinectes_sapidus) inhabit the bay. [147] Virginia is also home to 34 native species of crayfish, including the [Big Sandy crayfish](/Big_Sandy_crayfish). [148] [113] Amphibians found in Virginia include the [Cumberland Plateau salamander](/Cumberland_Plateau_salamander) and [Eastern hellbender](/Eastern_hellbender), [149] while the [northern watersnake](/Northern_watersnake) is the most common of the 32 snake species present. [150]

### Protected lands

*   See also: [List of Virginia state parks](/List_of_Virginia_state_parks)
*   [Oak](/Oak) trees release [isoprene](/Isoprene), contributing to the distinctive bluish haze observed in the [Blue Ridge Mountains](/Blue_Ridge_Mountains). [151]

As of 2019, approximately 16.2% of Virginia's land is under protection by federal, state, and local governments, as well as non-profit organizations. [152] Federal lands constitute the majority of protected areas, encompassing thirty units managed by the [National Park Service](/National_Park_Service), including [Great Falls Park](/Great_Falls_Park) and sections of the [Appalachian Trail](/Appalachian_Trail), as well as one national park, [Shenandoah](/Shenandoah_National_Park). [153] Nearly forty percent of Shenandoah National Park's total area of 199,173 acres (806 km 2 ) has been designated as wilderness under the [National Wilderness Preservation System](/National_Wilderness_Preservation_System). [154] The [U.S. Forest Service](/United_States_Forest_Service) oversees the [George Washington and Jefferson National Forests](/George_Washington_and_Jefferson_National_Forests), which collectively span over 1.6 million acres (6,500 km 2 ) within Virginia's mountainous regions and extend into [West Virginia](/West_Virginia) and [Kentucky](/Kentucky). [155] The [Great Dismal Swamp National Wildlife Refuge](/Great_Dismal_Swamp_National_Wildlife_Refuge) also extends into North Carolina, as does the [Back Bay National Wildlife Refuge](/Back_Bay_National_Wildlife_Refuge), marking the beginning of the [Outer Banks](/Outer_Banks). [156]

State agencies manage approximately one-third of the Commonwealth's protected lands. [152] The [Virginia Department of Conservation and Recreation](/Virginia_Department_of_Conservation_and_Recreation) oversees more than 75,900 acres (307.2 km 2 ) across forty [Virginia state parks](/List_of_Virginia_state_parks) and 65 [Natural Area Preserves](/Virginia_Natural_Area_Preserve_System), in addition to three undeveloped parks. [157] [158] [Breaks Interstate Park](/Breaks_Interstate_Park), which straddles the Kentucky border, is one of only two interstate parks in the United States. [159] Sustainable logging practices are permitted in 26 [state forests](/List_of_Virginia_state_forests) managed by the [Virginia Department of Forestry](/Virginia_Department_of_Forestry), covering a total of 71,972 acres (291.3 km 2 ). [160] Hunting is permitted in 44 [Wildlife Management Areas](/Virginia_Wildlife_Management_Areas) operated by the [Virginia Department of Wildlife Resources](/Virginia_Department_of_Wildlife_Resources), encompassing over 205,000 acres (829.6 km 2 ). [161] While the [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay) is not designated as a national park, it receives protection through both state and federal legislation, as well as the interstate [Chesapeake Bay Program](/Chesapeake_Bay_Program). [162]

### Cities and towns

*   See also: [Political subdivisions of Virginia](/Political_subdivisions_of_Virginia) and [Virginia statistical areas](/Virginia_statistical_areas)
*   The population density of Virginia counties and cities as of 2020.

Virginia is comprised of 95 [counties](/List_of_counties_in_Virginia) and 38 [independent cities](/Independent_city_(United_States)), which the [U.S. Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau) classifies as [county-equivalents](/County-equivalent). [163] This unique system of treating cities and counties as equivalent administrative units originated from the historical significance of [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia) and [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia) during the colonial era. [164] Only three other [independent cities](/Independent_city_(United_States)) exist elsewhere in the U.S. [165] The distinctions between counties and cities in Virginia are minor, pertaining primarily to their authority in assessing new taxes, the necessity of referendums for bond issuance, and the application of [Dillon's Rule](/Dillon%27s_Rule), which limits the powers of cities and counties to actions explicitly authorized by the [General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly). [166] [167] Counties may also incorporate [towns](/List_of_towns_in_Virginia). While there are no further [administrative subdivisions](/Administrative_divisions_of_Virginia), the Census Bureau recognizes several hundred [unincorporated communities](/List_of_unincorporated_communities_in_Virginia).

[Arlington County](/Arlington_County,_Virginia) in [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia) was formerly part of [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.).

Over three million people, constituting 35% of Virginia's population, reside in the twenty jurisdictions collectively defined as [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia). This region is part of the larger [Washington metropolitan area](/Washington_metropolitan_area) and the [Northeast megalopolis](/Northeast_megalopolis). [168] [169] [Fairfax County](/Fairfax_County,_Virginia), with a population exceeding 1.1 million, is Virginia's most populous jurisdiction [170] and features a major commercial and retail hub in [Tysons](/Tysons,_Virginia), which serves as Virginia's largest office market. [171] Neighboring [Prince William County](/Prince_William_County,_Virginia), with over 450,000 residents, ranks as Virginia's second most populous county and is home to [Marine Corps Base Quantico](/Marine_Corps_Base_Quantico), the [FBI Academy](/FBI_Academy), and [Manassas National Battlefield Park](/Manassas_National_Battlefield_Park). [Arlington County](/Arlington_County,_Virginia) holds the distinction of being the smallest self-governing county in the U.S. by land area, [172] and local officials have proposed its reorganization as an independent city due to its high population density. [166] [Loudoun County](/Loudoun_County,_Virginia) is recognized as the fastest-growing county in the state. [170] [173] In western Virginia, the city of [Roanoke](/Roanoke,_Virginia) and [Montgomery County](/Montgomery_County,_Virginia), part of the [Blacksburg–Christiansburg metropolitan area](/Blacksburg%E2%80%93Christiansburg_metropolitan_area), have both surpassed a population of 100,000 since 2018. [174]

Situated on the western edge of the [Tidewater region](/Tidewater_(region)) is Virginia's capital, [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia), with a city proper population of approximately 230,000 and a metropolitan area exceeding 1.3 million. On the eastern edge lies the [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads) metropolitan area, encompassing over 1.7 million residents across six counties and nine cities, including the Commonwealth's three most populous independent cities: [Virginia Beach](/Virginia_Beach,_Virginia), [Chesapeake](/Chesapeake,_Virginia), and [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia). [168] [175] The adjacent city of [Suffolk](/Suffolk,_Virginia), which includes a portion of the [Great Dismal Swamp](/Great_Dismal_Swamp), is the largest city by area, covering 429.1 square miles (1,111 km 2 ). [176] One factor contributing to the concentration of independent cities in the Tidewater region is the trend of several rural counties re-incorporating as cities or consolidating with existing ones to retain control over newly developed suburban neighborhoods that experienced growth in the 1950s. Cities like Norfolk and [Portsmouth](/Portsmouth,_Virginia) were historically able to annex land from adjacent counties until a moratorium was imposed in 1987. [177] Other cities, such as [Poquoson](/Poquoson,_Virginia), pursued city status as a means to preserve [racial segregation](/Racial_segregation) during the desegregation era of the 1970s. [178]

