*1790–2020,[179][180] 2024[3]*

The [2020 census](/2020_United_States_census) recorded Virginia's resident population at 8,631,393, representing a 7.9% increase since the [2010 census](/2010_United_States_census). An additional 23,149 Virginians reside overseas, bringing the state's total population to 8,654,542. Virginia ranks fourth among U.S. states for its overseas population, largely due to the presence of federal employees and military personnel. [181] As of 2020, Virginia's [fertility rate](/Fertility_rate) was 55.8 per 1,000 females aged 15 to 44. [182] The [median age](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_median_age) in 2021 was 38.8 years, aligning with the national average. [175] The geographic [center of population](/Center_of_population) was located northwest of [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia) in [Hanover County](/Hanover_County,_Virginia) as of 2020. [183]

Although Virginia continues to experience natural population growth due to births exceeding deaths, the state has recorded a negative [net migration rate](/Net_migration_rate) since 2013. In 2021, 8,995 more individuals departed the state than arrived. This trend is largely attributed to the high cost of housing in Northern Virginia, [184] which is prompting residents to relocate southward, with [Raleigh, North Carolina](/Raleigh,_North_Carolina) being a primary destination. [185] [186] Aside from Virginia, New York is the leading state of birth for Virginians, and the [Northeast](/Northeastern_United_States) region accounts for the largest number of domestic migrants entering the state. [187] Approximately twelve percent of Virginia residents were foreign-born as of 2020. [188] El Salvador is the most common country of origin for foreign-born residents, followed by [India](/India), [Mexico](/Mexico), [South Korea](/South_Korea), the [Philippines](/Philippines), and [Vietnam](/Vietnam). [188]

### Race and ethnicity

The state's largest demographic group, [non-Hispanic whites](/Non-Hispanic_whites), has seen a proportional decrease from 76% in 1990 to 58.6% in 2020. [189] [190] Immigrants from Britain and Ireland settled throughout the Commonwealth during the colonial period, [191] with roughly three-fourths arriving as [indentured servants](/Indentured_servant). [192] The Appalachian Mountains and [Shenandoah Valley](/Shenandoah_Valley) feature numerous settlements established by [German](/Shenandoah_Germans) and [Scotch-Irish immigrants](/Scotch-Irish_Americans) in the 18th and 19th centuries, often following the [Great Wagon Road](/Great_Wagon_Road). [193] [194] Over ten percent of Virginians reported German ancestry in 2020. [195]

New citizens participate in a naturalization ceremony in [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia), where 25% of residents are foreign-born, nearly double the state average. [188]

The most significant minority group in Virginia is the Black or African American population, comprising approximately one-fifth of the state's inhabitants. [190] Virginia was a major hub for the [Atlantic slave trade](/Atlantic_slave_trade). The [Igbo](/Igbo_American) ethnic group, originating from what is now southern [Nigeria](/Nigeria), represented the largest African contingent among enslaved individuals in Virginia. [196] Furthermore, Black Virginians exhibit greater European ancestry compared to those in other Southern states. DNA analyses reveal asymmetrical male and female ancestry predating the Civil War, indicating European fathers and African or Native American mothers. [197] [198] While the Black population experienced a decline due to the [Great Migration](/Great_Migration_(African_American)) to northern industrial cities in the first half of the 20th century, a reverse migration of Black individuals returning to the South has been observed since 1965. [199] The Commonwealth records the highest rate of Black-white [interracial marriages in the US](/Interracial_marriage_in_the_United_States), and 8.2% of Virginians identify as [multiracial](/Multiracial_people). [3]

Recent immigration since the late 20th century has led to the establishment of new Hispanic and Asian communities. As of 2020, 10.5% of Virginia's total population identified as [Hispanic or Latino](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans), and 8.8% identified as [Asian](/Asian_people). [3] The state's Hispanic population surged by 92% between 2000 and 2010, with two-thirds of this population residing in [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia). [201] Northern Virginia also hosts a substantial [Vietnamese American](/Vietnamese_American) population, with a major wave of immigration following the [Vietnam War](/Vietnam_War). [202] [Korean Americans](/Korean_American) have immigrated more recently, [203] while approximately 45,000 [Filipino Americans](/Filipino_American) have settled in the Hampton Roads area. [204]

Governor [Glenn Youngkin](/Glenn_Youngkin) receives a ceremonial tribute from representatives of the [Mattaponi](/Mattaponi) and [Pamunkey](/Pamunkey) tribes, a Thanksgiving tradition dating back to 1677. [205]

[Tribal membership in Virginia](/Native_American_tribes_in_Virginia) is complicated by the legacy of the state's "pencil genocide," a policy enacted through the [Racial Integrity Act of 1924](/Racial_Integrity_Act_of_1924) that intentionally categorized Native Americans and Black individuals together. Consequently, many tribal members possess African or European ancestry, or both. [206] In the 2020 U.S. Census, only 0.5% of Virginians identified exclusively as [American Indian](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) or [Alaska Native], although 2.1% reported this in combination with other ethnicities. [190] The state government has extended recognition to eleven tribes, and seven tribes also hold federal recognition. [207] [208] The [Pamunkey](/Pamunkey) and [Mattaponi](/Mattaponi) tribes maintain reservations situated on tributaries of the [York River](/York_River_(Virginia)) in the [Tidewater region](/Tidewater_region_of_Virginia). [209]

