### Languages

A recording of a resident from [Tangier Island](/Tangier,_Virginia), born in the late 1800s, demonstrates the island's distinctive accent.

According to U.S. Census data from 2022, 83% (6,805,548) of Virginia residents aged five and older speak [English](/English_language) at home as their [first language](/First_language). [Spanish](/Spanish_language) is the second most common language, spoken in 7.5% (611,831) of Virginia households. This figure rises to 8.7% (120,560) among Virginians under the age of eighteen. [Arabic](/Arabic_language) ranks as the third most frequently spoken language, with approximately 0.8% of residents, followed by [Chinese languages](/Chinese_language) and [Vietnamese](/Vietnamese_language), each spoken by over 0.7% of the population. [Korean](/Korean_language) and [Tagalog](/Tagalog_language) are spoken by just under 0.7% and 0.6% of residents, respectively. [210]

English was formally designated as the Commonwealth's official language through statutes enacted in 1981 and again in 1996, although this status is not constitutionally mandated. [211] While a more standardized [American English](/American_English) is prevalent in urban areas, and the use of Southern accents has generally declined among individuals born since the 1960s, [212] a variety of distinct accents persist. [213] The [Piedmont](/Piedmont_region_of_Virginia) region is noted for its non-rhotic dialect, which has significantly influenced [Southern American English](/Southern_American_English). A 2014 study by [BBC America](/BBC_America) identified it as one of the most recognizable accents in American English. [214] The [Tidewater accent](/Tidewater_accent) evolved from the speech patterns of the upper class in early colonial England, whereas the [Appalachian accent](/Appalachian_English) reflects a stronger influence from the English spoken by Scottish and Irish immigrants of that era. [213] [215] However, [Appalachian stereotypes](/Appalachian_stereotypes) have led some individuals from the region to adopt a less distinct English accent through [code-switching](/Code-switching). [216] The English spoken on [Tangier Island](/Tangier,_Virginia) in the [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay), preserved by the island's isolation, retains numerous phrases and euphemisms unique to the location and exhibits elements of [Early Modern English](/Early_Modern_English). [217] [218]

