Virginia enshrined the principle of [religious freedom](/Freedom_of_religion) through a [statute in 1786](/Virginia_Statute_for_Religious_Freedom). Although historically situated within America's [Bible Belt](/Bible_Belt), a 2023 survey by the [Public Religion Research Institute](/Public_Religion_Research_Institute) (PRRI) estimated that 55% of Virginians seldom or never attend religious services, exceeding the national average of 53.2%. The survey also indicated an increase in the percentage of Virginians unaffiliated with any religious body, rising from 21% in 2013 to 29% in 2023. [219] The 2020 U.S. Religion Census, conducted by the [Association of Religion Data Archives](/Association_of_Religion_Data_Archives) (ARDA), similarly found that 55% of Virginians do not attend any of the state's 10,477 congregations. [220] Overall [belief in God](/Belief_in_God) has also seen a decline across the [South region](/Southern_United_States), of which Virginia is a part, dropping from 93% of respondents in [Gallup](/Gallup,_Inc.) surveys conducted between 2013 and 2017 to 86% in 2022. [221]

In the 2020 ARDA census, [Evangelical Protestants](/Evangelicalism) constituted the largest religious grouping among the 45% of Virginians affiliated with religious bodies, representing 20.3% of the state's population. [Mainline Protestants](/Mainline_Protestant) accounted for 8.1%, and [Black Protestants](/Black_church) for 2%. [Baptists](/Baptists), 84% of whom are categorized as Evangelical, comprised 9.4% of Virginians in that census. The primary divisions within the Baptist denomination are between the [Baptist General Association of Virginia](/Baptist_General_Association_of_Virginia), established in 1823, and the [Southern Baptist Conservatives of Virginia](/Southern_Baptist_Conservatives_of_Virginia), which separated in 1996. Other Protestant denominations with over one percent of Virginia's population include [Pentecostalism](/Pentecostalism) (1.8%), [Presbyterianism](/Presbyterianism) (1.3%), [Anglicanism](/Anglicanism) (1.2%), and [Adventism](/Adventism) (1%). [222] The 2023 PRRI survey estimated that 46% of Virginians identify as Protestants, with 14% each categorized as White Evangelical, White Mainline, and Black, although these figures include individuals who report no regular attendance at services. [219]

Since 1927, [Arlington National Cemetery](/Arlington_National_Cemetery) in [Arlington County, Virginia](/Arlington_County,_Virginia) has hosted an annual nondenominational [sunrise service](/Sunrise_service) on Easter Sunday. [223]

[Catholics](/Roman_Catholicism_in_the_United_States) represented 10.3% of the population in the 2020 ARDA census, [222] and 16% in the 2023 PRRI survey, which further divided them into 9% White Catholic, 6% Hispanic Catholic, and 1% other. [219] Catholic churches in Virginia are organized under either the [Diocese of Arlington](/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Arlington) or the [Diocese of Richmond](/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Richmond). Episcopal churches fall under the [Episcopal Diocese of Virginia](/Episcopal_Diocese_of_Virginia), the [Episcopal Diocese of Southern Virginia](/Episcopal_Diocese_of_Southern_Virginia), and the [Episcopal Diocese of Southwestern Virginia](/Episcopal_Diocese_of_Southwestern_Virginia). Adherents of [the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints](/The_Church_of_Jesus_Christ_of_Latter-day_Saints) constitute just over one percent of the population, with 210 [congregations in Virginia](/The_Church_of_Jesus_Christ_of_Latter-day_Saints_in_Virginia) as of 2024. [224] While Virginia's Jewish population is relatively small, organized Jewish sites date back to 1789 with the founding of [Congregation Beth Ahabah](/Congregation_Beth_Ahabah). [225]

[Fairfax County](/Fairfax_County,_Virginia) stands out as the state's most religiously diverse jurisdiction. [220] [Fairfax Station](/Fairfax_Station,_Virginia) is home to the [Ekoji Buddhist Temple](/Ekoji_Buddhist_Temple), affiliated with the [Jōdo Shinshū](/J%C5%8Ddo_Shinsh%C5%AB) school, and the Hindu [Durga Temple of Virginia](/Durga_Temple_of_Virginia). The [All Dulles Area Muslim Society](/All_Dulles_Area_Muslim_Society), located on the county's border in [Sterling](/Sterling,_Virginia), comprises eleven branches and is considered the second-largest [Muslim](/Muslim) mosque community in the country. [226] [McLean Bible Church](/McLean_Bible_Church), with approximately 16,500 weekly attendees, ranks among the top 25 largest [megachurches](/Megachurch) in the U.S. According to the 2020 ARDA census, 8.4% of Virginians attend [nondenominational Christian](/Nondenominational_Christianity) churches similar to McLean Bible Church. [227] [222] In that same census, the metropolitan areas of [Lynchburg](/Lynchburg_metropolitan_area) and [Roanoke](/Roanoke_metropolitan_area) reported the highest rates of religious adherence, while the state-college-dominated [Blacksburg–Christiansburg](/Blacksburg%E2%80%93Christiansburg_metropolitan_area) and [Charlottesville](/Charlottesville,_Virginia_metropolitan_area) recorded the lowest. [222] Two prominent Christian universities, [Liberty University](/Liberty_University) and the [University of Lynchburg](/University_of_Lynchburg), are based in Lynchburg, while [Regent University](/Regent_University) is located in [Virginia Beach](/Virginia_Beach,_Virginia).

### Economy

*   Main article: [Economy of Virginia](/Economy_of_Virginia)
*   See also: [Virginia locations by per capita income](/Virginia_locations_by_per_capita_income)
*   Counties and cities by median [property tax](/Property_tax) paid in 2019.

Virginia's economy is sustained by a diverse range of sectors, including local and federal government, military operations, agriculture, and high-technology industries. In 2022, the state's [average per capita income](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_income) was $68,211, [228] and its [gross domestic product](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_GDP) (GDP) reached $654.5 billion, placing both figures among the top 13 highest for U.S. states. [229] The [COVID-19 recession](/COVID-19_recession) led to a surge in jobless claims, exceeding 10% in early April 2020, [230] before returning to pre-pandemic levels in 2023. [231] As of March 2025, the unemployment rate stood at 3.2%, ranking as the 11th lowest nationwide. [232]

Virginia boasts a [median household income](/Median_household_income) of $89,931 as of 2023, [4] ranking 11th nationally. The state's poverty rate is 10.2%, placing it among the [10th-lowest nationwide](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_poverty_rate). [3] [Montgomery County](/Montgomery_County,_Virginia) near [Blacksburg](/Blacksburg,_Virginia) exhibits the state's highest poverty rate, with 28.5% of its population falling below the [U.S. Census poverty thresholds](/Poverty_thresholds_(United_States_Census_Bureau)). Conversely, [Loudoun County](/Loudoun_County,_Virginia) registers the highest median household income in the nation, and the broader [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia) region is recognized as one of the highest-income regions nationwide. [233] As of 2022, eighteen of the hundred [highest-income counties in the United States](/Highest-income_counties_in_the_United_States), including the top two, are situated in Northern Virginia. [234] While [median home prices](/List_of_U.S._states_by_median_home_price) in Virginia generally surpass the national average, particularly in Northern Virginia where they were 44.8% higher in May 2024 at $760,000, [235] 69.1% of [Virginians own their homes](/Housing_in_Virginia) as of 2023. [236] The [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads) region reports the state's highest per capita number of homeless individuals, with 11 per 10,000 residents as of 2020. [237] Despite a lower [Gini index](/List_of_U.S._states_by_Gini_coefficient) indicating less [income inequality](/Income_inequality) than the national average, [238] Virginia's middle class is smaller relative to most other states. [239]

[CNBC](/CNBC) recognized Virginia as its 2024 [Top State for Business](/America%27s_Top_States_For_Business), citing deductions primarily for the high costs associated with business and living. [240] [Forbes](/Forbes) magazine ranked it sixteenth for ease of starting a business. [241] However, [Oxfam America](/Oxfam_America) ranked Virginia 26th overall in its 2024 assessment of states for workers, noting strengths in protections against sexual harassment and [pregnancy discrimination](/Pregnancy_discrimination), but weaknesses in laws governing organized labor and a low minimum wage for tipped employees ($2.13). [242] Virginia has maintained an [employment-at-will](/At-will_employment) policy since 1906 and a "[right to work](/Right-to-work_law)" status since 1947. [243] [244] Although the state minimum wage increased to $12 in 2023, farmworkers and tipped employees are specifically excluded from this increase. [245] [242]

#### Government agencies

The [U.S. Department of Defense](/United_States_Department_of_Defense) is headquartered in [Arlington County](/Arlington_County,_Virginia) at [the Pentagon](/The_Pentagon).

As of 2022, government agencies directly employ approximately 714,100 Virginians, constituting nearly 17% of the state's total workforce. [246] Virginia receives the second-largest share of [U.S. federal procurement](/Government_procurement_in_the_United_States) funds after [California], amounting to about 12% of all federal spending. [247] [248] In 2020, the [U.S. Department of Defense](/U.S._Department_of_Defense) employed 125,648 active-duty personnel, 25,404 reservists, and 99,832 civilians at [the Pentagon](/The_Pentagon) or one of the state's 27 military bases, which collectively occupy 270,009 acres (1,092.69 km 2 ). [249] An additional 139,000 Virginians are employed by [defense contracting](/Government_contractor) firms, [250] which received $44.8 billion in contracts during the 2020 fiscal year. [249] Virginia has the second-highest concentration of veterans among U.S. states, with 9.7% of its population being veterans. The [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads) area hosts the world's largest naval base and the only [NATO](/NATO) installation on U.S. soil, [Naval Station Norfolk](/Naval_Station_Norfolk). [251] [249]

Other significant [federal agencies located in Northern Virginia](/List_of_federal_agencies_in_Northern_Virginia) include the [Central Intelligence Agency](/Central_Intelligence_Agency) in [Langley](/Langley,_Virginia), the [National Science Foundation](/National_Science_Foundation) and the [U.S. Patent and Trademark Office](/United_States_Patent_and_Trademark_Office) in [Alexandria](/Alexandria,_Virginia), the [U.S. Geological Survey](/United_States_Geological_Survey) in [Reston](/Reston,_Virginia), and the [U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service](/United_States_Fish_%26_Wildlife_Service) in [Bailey's Crossroads](/Bailey%27s_Crossroads,_Virginia). Virginia's state government employs over 106,000 public servants, whose median income was $52,401 as of 2018. [252] The [Virginia Department of Transportation](/Virginia_Department_of_Transportation) and the [Virginia Department of Education](/Virginia_Department_of_Education) are the two largest state departments by expenditure. [253] K–12 teachers in Virginia earn an average annual salary of $59,970, which ranks as the thirteenth lowest in the U.S. when adjusted for the state's [cost of living](/Cost_of_living) as of the 2021–22 school year. [254]

#### Business

Ocean tourism is a significant component of [Virginia Beach's](/Virginia_Beach,_Virginia) economy.

As of 2020, Virginia is home to 204,131 independent employers and 644,341 [sole proprietorships](/Sole_proprietorship). Among the 144,431 registered non-farm businesses in 2017, 59.4% were majority male-owned, 22% were majority female-owned, 19.6% were majority minority-owned, and 8.9% were veteran-owned. [3] As of 2024, twenty-four [Fortune 500](/Fortune_500) companies are headquartered in Virginia, with the largest firms by revenue including [Freddie Mac](/Freddie_Mac), [Boeing](/Boeing), [RTX Corporation](/RTX_Corporation), [Performance Food Group](/Performance_Food_Group), and [Capital One](/Capital_One). [255] The two largest companies by employee count are [Dollar Tree](/Dollar_Tree) in [Chesapeake](/Chesapeake,_Virginia) and [Hilton Worldwide Holdings](/Hilton_Worldwide_Holdings) in [McLean](/McLean,_Virginia). [256]

Virginia ranks third nationally in the concentration of technology workers and fifth in the overall number of tech workers as of 2020. [257] The 451,268 tech jobs in the state represent 11.1% of all employment and yield a median salary of $98,292. [257] A significant portion of these jobs are located in [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia), which hosts numerous software, communications, and cybersecurity companies, particularly within the [Dulles Technology Corridor](/Dulles_Technology_Corridor) and [Tysons](/Tysons,_Virginia) areas. In 2018, [Amazon](/Amazon_(company)) selected [Crystal City](/Crystal_City,_Virginia) for [its HQ2](/Amazon_HQ2), and [Google](/Google) expanded its [Reston](/Reston,_Virginia) offices in 2019.

Northern Virginia emerged as the world's largest [data center](/Data_center) market in 2016, encompassing over 47.7 million square feet (4.43 km 2 ) as of 2023. [258] Much of this development is concentrated in [Loudoun County](/Loudoun_County,_Virginia), which has branded itself as "Data Center Alley." [259] [260] Data centers in Virginia handle approximately one-third of all internet traffic, directly employing 13,500 Virginians in 2023 and supporting a total of 45,000 jobs. [261] Virginia recorded the second-fastest average internet speed among U.S. states that year and ranked ninth for household broadband access at 93.6%. [262] [263] [Computer chips](/Integrated_circuit) became the state's highest-grossing export in 2006, [264] with an estimated export value of $740 million in 2022. [265] While ranking in the top quartile for diversity based on the [Simpson index](/Simpson_index), only 26% of Virginia's tech employees are women, and 13% are Black or African American. [257]

Tourist spending in Virginia reached a record $33.3 billion in 2023, marking a 10% increase from the previous year and supporting an estimated 224,000 jobs, an increase of 13,000. [266] In 2022, the state ranked as the eighth most visited in the U.S. [267] That year, Virginia welcomed 745,000 international visitors, with 41% originating from [Canada](/Canada). [268]

#### Agriculture

[Rockingham County](/Rockingham_County,_Virginia) in the [Shenandoah Valley](/Shenandoah_Valley) accounts for twenty percent of Virginia's agricultural sales as of 2017, with the valley region as a whole being the state's most productive agricultural area. [269]

As of 2021, agriculture occupies 30% of Virginia's land, encompassing 7.7 million acres (12,031 sq mi; 31,161 km 2 ) of farmland. Nearly 54,000 Virginians are employed on the state's 41,500 farms, which average 186 acres (0.29 sq mi; 0.75 km 2 ). Although agriculture has experienced a substantial decline since 1960, when the number of farms was twice as high, it remains Virginia's largest industry, generating over 490,000 jobs. [270] Soybeans were the most profitable single crop in Virginia in 2022, [271] although the ongoing [trade war with China](/China%E2%80%93United_States_trade_war) has prompted many Virginia farmers to shift to cotton cultivation. [272] Other leading agricultural products include corn, cut flowers, and tobacco, with Virginia ranking third nationally in [tobacco production](/Cultivation_of_tobacco). [270] [271]

Virginia ranks as the country's third-largest producer of seafood as of 2021. [273] The primary seafood harvests by value include [sea scallops](/Placopecten_magellanicus), oysters, [Chesapeake blue crabs](/Callinectes_sapidus), [menhaden](/Menhaden), and hardshell clams. Top export destinations for Virginia seafood are [France](/France), [Canada](/Canada), [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), and [Hong Kong](/Hong_Kong). Commercial fishing supports 18,220 jobs as of 2020, while recreational fishing contributes another 5,893 jobs. [274] The population of [eastern oysters](/Eastern_oyster) experienced a collapse in the 1980s due to pollution and overharvesting but has shown a gradual recovery. The 2022–2023 season recorded the largest oyster harvest in 35 years, yielding approximately 700,000 U.S. bushels (25,000 kL). [275] A mild winter and dry summer resulted in one of the best wine harvests in recent years for vineyards in the [Northern Neck](/Northern_Neck) and along the [Blue Ridge Mountains](/Blue_Ridge_Mountains), areas that also attract 2.6 million tourists annually. [276] [277] Virginia ranks seventh nationally with 388 wineries producing 1.1 million cases annually as of 2024. [278] Virginia breweries produced 460,315 barrels (54,017 kl) of craft beer in 2022, placing it 15th among U.S. states. [279]

#### Taxes

Counties and cities by median [property tax](/Property_tax) paid in 2019.

[State income tax](/State_income_tax) is levied on individuals whose incomes exceed a specified [filing threshold](/Tax_return_(United_States)). Virginia employs a progressive tax system with five income brackets, with tax rates ranging from 2.0% to 5.75% of taxable income. [280] [281] The [state sales](/Sales_taxes_in_the_United_States) and [use tax](/Use_tax) rate is 4.3%, supplemented by an additional 1% local tax, resulting in a combined sales tax rate of 5.3% on most transactions. Three specific regions are subject to a higher sales tax: 6% in Northern Virginia and Hampton Roads, and 7% in the [Historic Triangle](/Historic_Triangle). [282] Unlike most states, Virginia imposes a 1% sales tax on groceries, [283] which was reduced from 2.5% in January 2023, with the scope of this lower tax rate expanded to include essential personal hygiene products. [282] [284]

[Property tax](/Property_tax_in_the_United_States) rates in Virginia are determined and collected at the local government level and vary across the Commonwealth. Real estate is also subject to local taxation. [285] As of 2021, the statewide median real estate tax rate was $0.96 per $100 of assessed taxable value. However, for 72 of the 95 counties, this rate was below $0.80 per $100. Northern Virginia exhibits the highest property taxes in the state, with [Manassas Park](/Manassas_Park,_Virginia) having the highest effective tax rate at $1.31 per $100, while [Powhatan](/Powhatan_County,_Virginia) and [Lunenburg](/Lunenburg_County,_Virginia) counties share the lowest rate at $0.30. [286] Of the total local government tax revenue, approximately 61% is generated from real property taxes, with tangible personal property, sales and use, and business license taxes contributing 24%. The remaining 15% derives from [taxes on hotels](/Hotel_tax), restaurant meals, public service corporation property, and consumer utilities. [285]

## Culture

*   Main article: [Culture of Virginia](/Culture_of_Virginia)
*   Colonial Virginian culture, language, and aesthetics are recreated in [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg).

Modern Virginian culture draws from numerous sources and is recognized as part of the broader [culture of the Southern United States](/Culture_of_the_Southern_United_States). [287] The [Smithsonian Institution](/Smithsonian_Institution) delineates Virginia into nine distinct cultural regions. [288]

Beyond the general [cuisine of the Southern United States](/Cuisine_of_the_Southern_United_States), Virginians maintain unique culinary traditions. [Virginia wine](/Virginia_wine) is produced across various regions of the Commonwealth. [277] [Smithfield ham], often referred to as "Virginia ham," is a specific type of [country ham](/Country_ham) that is legally protected by state law and can only be produced in the town of [Smithfield, Virginia](/Smithfield,_Virginia). [289] [Virginia furniture](/Virginia_furniture) and architectural styles are characteristic of [American colonial architecture](/American_colonial_architecture). Thomas Jefferson and many of Virginia's early leaders favored the [Neoclassical architecture](/Neoclassical_architecture) style, influencing its adoption for prominent state buildings. Elements of [Pennsylvania Dutch](/Pennsylvania_Dutch) culture and architectural style are also present in certain areas of the Commonwealth. [193]

Virginia's literary landscape frequently explores the Commonwealth's historical narrative. The works of [Pulitzer Prize](/Pulitzer_Prize) recipient [Ellen Glasgow](/Ellen_Glasgow) often examined social inequalities and the societal role of women in her cultural context. [290] [James Branch Cabell](/James_Branch_Cabell) extensively documented the evolving position of the gentry during the [Reconstruction era](/Reconstruction_era), challenging its moral codes through works like [Jurgen, A Comedy of Justice](/Jurgen,_A_Comedy_of_Justice). [291] [William Styron] (/William_Styron) delved into historical themes in novels such as [The Confessions of Nat Turner](/The_Confessions_of_Nat_Turner_(1967)) and [Sophie's Choice](/Sophie%27s_Choice_(novel)). [292] [Tom Wolfe](/Tom_Wolfe) has occasionally addressed his Southern heritage in best-selling novels like [I Am Charlotte Simmons](/I_Am_Charlotte_Simmons). [293] [Matt Bondurant](/Matt_Bondurant) garnered critical acclaim for his [historical novel](/Historical_fiction) [The Wettest County in the World], which depicted moonshiners in [Franklin County, Virginia](/Franklin_County,_Virginia) during [Prohibition](/Prohibition_in_the_United_States). [294] Virginia also designates a [Poet Laureate of Virginia](/Poet_Laureate_of_Virginia). [295]

### Fine and performing arts

*   See also: [Music of Virginia](/Music_of_Virginia)
*   [The Steel Wheels](/The_Steel_Wheels), an Americana roots folk rock band, performs at [Jefferson Theater](/Jefferson_Theater_(Virginia)) in [Charlottesville](/Charlottesville,_Virginia) in February 2019.

Virginia ranks near the national average in public spending on the arts as of 2021, at just over half of the national average. [296] The state government supports several cultural institutions, including the [Virginia Museum of Fine Arts](/Virginia_Museum_of_Fine_Arts) and the [Science Museum of Virginia](/Science_Museum_of_Virginia). Other notable museums include the [Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center](/Steven_F._Udvar-Hazy_Center) of the [National Air and Space Museum](/National_Air_and_Space_Museum) and the [Chrysler Museum of Art](/Chrysler_Museum_of_Art). [297] In addition to these institutions, Virginia hosts numerous open-air museums and living history sites, such as [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg), the [Frontier Culture Museum](/Frontier_Culture_Museum_of_Virginia), and various historic battlefields. [298] The [Virginia Foundation for the Humanities](/Virginia_Foundation_for_the_Humanities) is dedicated to enhancing the Commonwealth's civic, cultural, and intellectual landscape. [299]

The [Harrison Opera House](/Harrison_Opera_House) in [Norfolk, Virginia](/Norfolk,_Virginia) is the home venue for the [Virginia Opera](/Virginia_Opera). The [Virginia Symphony Orchestra](/Virginia_Symphony_Orchestra) performs throughout the [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads) area. [300] Resident and touring theater companies operate out of the [American Shakespeare Center](/American_Shakespeare_Center) in [Staunton, Virginia](/Staunton,_Virginia). [301] The [Barter Theatre](/Barter_Theatre) in [Abingdon, Virginia](/Abingdon,_Virginia), designated as the State Theatre of Virginia, received the first [Regional Theatre Tony Award](/Regional_Theatre_Tony_Award) in 1948. The [Signature Theatre](/Signature_Theatre_(Arlington,_Virginia)) in [Arlington, Virginia](/Arlington_County,_Virginia) was honored with the award in 2009. Additionally, [Theatre IV](/Theatre_IV), the second-largest touring troupe in the nation, serves as Virginia's Children's Theater. [302] Notable music performance venues include [The Birchmere](/The_Birchmere), the [Landmark Theater](/Landmark_Theater_(Richmond,_Virginia)), and [Jiffy Lube Live](/Jiffy_Lube_Live). [303] [Wolf Trap National Park for the Performing Arts], located in [Vienna, Virginia](/Vienna,_Virginia), is the only national park designated for performing arts activities. [304]

Virginia is renowned for its contributions to [old-time string](/Old-time_music) and [bluegrass](/Bluegrass_music) genres, with influential groups such as the [Carter Family](/Carter_Family) and the [Stanley Brothers](/Stanley_Brothers) achieving national recognition in the 1940s. [305] The state's African American musical heritage is represented through [gospel](/Gospel_(music)), [blues](/Blues), and [shout bands](/Shout_band). Both [Ella Fitzgerald](/Ella_Fitzgerald) and [Pearl Bailey](/Pearl_Bailey) hailed from [Newport News, Virginia](/Newport_News,_Virginia). [306] Contemporary Virginia artists have also gained prominence, including [folk rock](/Folk_rock) musicians like [Dave Matthews](/Dave_Matthews) and [Jason Mraz](/Jason_Mraz); [R&B](/Contemporary_R%26B) artists such as [Chris Brown](/Chris_Brown), [D'Angelo](/D%27Angelo), and [Kali Uchis](/Kali_Uchis); [hip hop](/Hip_hop_music) stars like [Pharrell Williams](/Pharrell_Williams), [Timbaland](/Timbaland), [Missy Elliott](/Missy_Elliott), and [Pusha T](/Pusha_T); and [thrash metal](/Thrash_metal) bands including [GWAR](/GWAR) and [Lamb of God](/Lamb_of_God_(band)). [307] Several members of the [country music](/Country_music) band [Old Dominion](/Old_Dominion_(band)) grew up in the [Roanoke](/Roanoke,_Virginia) area and adopted their band name from Virginia's state nickname. [308]

### Festivals

The annual [Pony Penning](/Pony_Penning) event features over 200 [Chincoteague ponies](/Chincoteague_Pony) swimming across the [Assateague Channel](/Assateague_Channel) to [Chincoteague, Virginia](/Chincoteague,_Virginia). [309]

Numerous counties and localities across Virginia host [county fairs](/County_fair) and festivals. The [Virginia State Fair](/Virginia_State_Fair) takes place annually in September at the [Meadow Event Park](/Meadow_Event_Park). Also in September, the [Neptune Festival](/Neptune_Festival) in [Virginia Beach, Virginia](/Virginia_Beach,_Virginia) celebrates the city, its waterfront, and regional artists. [Norfolk's Harborfest](/Norfolk,_Virginia), held in June, showcases boat races and [air shows](/Air_show). [Fairfax County](/Fairfax_County,_Virginia) sponsors "Celebrate Fairfax!", featuring popular and traditional music performances. [311] The Virginia Lake Festival is held in July in [Clarksville, Virginia](/Clarksville,_VA). [312] The island of [Chincoteague](/Chincoteague,_Virginia) on the [Eastern Shore of Virginia](/Eastern_Shore_of_Virginia) hosts the annual [Pony Penning](/Pony_Penning) event for feral [Chincoteague ponies](/Chincoteague_Pony), which has expanded into a week-long carnival. [309] Every Thanksgiving in [Richmond, Virginia](/Richmond,_Virginia), the [Mattaponi](/Mattaponi) and [Pamunkey](/Pamunkey) tribes present Virginia's governor with a ceremonial tribute of deer, honoring colonial treaties. [205]

The [Shenandoah Apple Blossom Festival](/Shenandoah_Apple_Blossom_Festival) is a two-week event held annually in [Winchester, Virginia](/Winchester,_Virginia), featuring parades and [bluegrass](/Bluegrass_music) concerts. The Old Time Fiddlers' Convention in [Galax, Virginia](/Galax,_Virginia), established in 1935, is recognized as one of the oldest and largest such events globally. Wolf Trap hosts the [Wolf Trap Opera Company](/Wolf_Trap_Opera_Company), which presents an opera festival each summer. [304] The Blue Ridge Rock Festival, initiated in 2017, has attracted up to 33,000 attendees to the Blue Ridge Amphitheater in [Pittsylvania County, Virginia](/Pittsylvania_County,_Virginia). [313] Two prominent film festivals, the [Virginia Film Festival](/Virginia_Film_Festival) and the [VCU French Film Festival], are held annually in [Charlottesville, Virginia](/Charlottesville,_Virginia) and Richmond, respectively. [314]

## Law and government

*   Main article: [Government of Virginia](/Government_of_Virginia)
*   The [Virginia State Capitol](/Virginia_State_Capitol) in [Richmond, Virginia](/Richmond,_Virginia), designed by [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson) and [Charles-Louis Clérisseau](/Charles-Louis_Cl%C3%A9risseau), houses the [Virginia General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly).

The first meeting of the [Virginia General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly) occurred in 1619, establishing Virginia's legislature as the oldest of its kind in North America. [315] The current governmental framework operates under the seventh [Constitution of Virginia](/Constitution_of_Virginia), approved by voters in 1970 and effective from July 1971. [78] This constitution mirrors the [federal structure](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States) by establishing three branches of government: a robust legislature, an executive branch, and a unified judicial system. [316]

Virginia's legislature is [bicameral](/Bicameral), consisting of a 100-member [House of Delegates](/Virginia_House_of_Delegates) and a 40-member [Senate](/Senate_of_Virginia). These bodies collaboratively draft legislation for the Commonwealth. Delegates serve two-year terms, while senators serve four-year terms. [The most recent elections](/2025_Virginia_elections) for the House were held in November 2023, and for the Senate in November 2025. The executive branch comprises the [Governor](/Governor_of_Virginia), [Lieutenant Governor](/Lieutenant_Governor_of_Virginia), and [Attorney General](/Attorney_General_of_Virginia), all elected to four-year terms in separate elections. [The most recent elections](/2025_Virginia_gubernatorial_election) for these offices occurred in November 2025. Governors are constitutionally prohibited from seeking immediate re-election but may serve non-consecutive terms. [317] The Lieutenant Governor serves as the official president of the Senate, casting tie-breaking votes. The House elects a [Speaker of the House](/List_of_Speakers_of_the_Virginia_House_of_Delegates), and the Senate elects a [President pro tempore](/President_pro_tempore_of_the_Senate_of_Virginia) to preside in the Lieutenant Governor's absence. Both chambers also elect their respective clerks and majority and minority leaders. [318] The Governor appoints 16 [cabinet members](/Virginia_Governor%27s_Cabinet) and heads of various state departments. [319]

The legislature convenes for regular sessions on the second Wednesday of each year. Sessions last up to 48 days in odd-numbered years (election years) or 60 days in even-numbered years, allowing for the consideration of biennial state budgets proposed by the governor. [318] [320] Following the conclusion of regular sessions, special sessions can be convened either by the governor or with the agreement of two-thirds of both legislative houses. Since 2000, 21 special sessions have been called, typically to address pre-determined legislative agendas. [321] Although not a full-time legislature, the General Assembly is considered hybrid due to the absence of constitutional limits on special session durations, which often extend for several months. [322] A one-day "veto session" is automatically convened when the governor chooses to veto legislation or return bills with amendments. Vetoes can be overridden by a two-thirds majority vote in both the House and the Senate. [323] Bills that pass with a two-thirds majority can become law without the governor's signature. [324] Virginia does not have a "[pocket veto](/Pocket_veto)"; bills automatically become law if the governor neither approves nor vetoes them. [325]

### Legal system

Unlike the [federal judiciary system](/Federal_judiciary_of_the_United_States), justices of the [Virginia Supreme Court](/Supreme_Court_of_Virginia) are subject to term limits, a mandatory retirement age, and select their own Chief Justice.

Virginia's judicial system, the oldest in the United States, comprises judges and justices who are elected by a majority vote in both the House and the Senate, without gubernatorial input—a mechanism that underscores the legislature's significant authority over the judiciary. The governor can make [recess appointments](/Recess_appointment), and when both branches are controlled by the same party, the assembly often confirms these appointments. The judicial hierarchy begins with the [General District Courts](/Virginia_General_District_Court) and [Juvenile and Domestic Relations District Courts](/Virginia_Juvenile_and_Domestic_Relations_District_Court), followed by the [Circuit Courts](/Virginia_Circuit_Court), the [Court of Appeals of Virginia](/Court_of_Appeals_of_Virginia), and culminating with the [Supreme Court of Virginia](/Supreme_Court_of_Virginia) at the apex. [326] The Supreme Court consists of seven justices who serve 12-year terms and must retire at age 73. They elect their own chief justice, whose tenure is informally limited to two four-year terms. [327] Virginia was the last state to guarantee an automatic right of [appeal](/Appeal) in all civil and criminal cases. In 2021, the number of judges on the Court of Appeals increased from 11 to 17. [328] [329]

The [Code of Virginia](/Code_of_Virginia) codifies the statutory law enacted by the General Assembly. The [Virginia State Police](/Virginia_State_Police) is the largest [law enforcement agency in Virginia](/List_of_law_enforcement_agencies_in_Virginia), comprising 3,035 sworn and civilian members as of 2019. [330] The [Virginia Marine Police](/Virginia_Marine_Police), originally established as the "Oyster Navy" in 1864, was formed in response to widespread [oyster bed poaching](/Oyster_pirate). [331] The [Virginia Division of Capitol Police](/Virginia_Division_of_Capitol_Police) provides security for the legislature and executive branch and is recognized as the oldest police department in the United States, tracing its origins to the guards who protected colonial leadership. [332] The governor can also mobilize the [Virginia National Guard](/Virginia_National_Guard), which includes approximately 7,200 [army soldiers](/Virginia_Army_National_Guard), 1,200 [airmen](/Virginia_Air_National_Guard), 300 [Defense Force members](/Virginia_Defense_Force), and 400 civilians. [333]

Between 1608 and 2021, when the [death penalty](/Capital_punishment_in_Virginia) was abolished, Virginia executed over 1,300 individuals, including 113 following the resumption of capital punishment in 1982. [List of people executed in Virginia] [334] As of 2018, Virginia's prison system incarcerates 30,936 individuals, 53% of whom are Black. [335] The state has the sixteenth-highest [incarceration rate in the country](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_incarceration_and_correctional_supervision_rate), at 422 per 100,000 residents. [336] Prisoner [parole](/Parole) was eliminated in 1995. [337] Virginia's [recidivism rate](/Recidivism) for released felons reconvicted within three years and sentenced to a year or more stands at 23.1%, the lowest in the nation as of 2019. [338] [339] Virginia reports the fourth-lowest violent crime rate and the thirteenth-lowest property crime rate as of 2018. [340] Between 2008 and 2017, arrests for drug-related offenses increased by 38%, with 71% of these related to [marijuana](/Cannabis_in_Virginia). [341] Virginia decriminalized marijuana in July 2020 and legalized it in July 2021. [342] [343]

### Politics

*   Main article: [Politics of Virginia](/Politics_of_Virginia)
*   Reflecting Virginia's political evolution, the annual [Shad Planking](/Shad_Planking) event in [Wakefield, Virginia](/Wakefield,_Virginia) has transformed from a remnant of the [Byrd era](/Byrd_Organization) into a regular stop for numerous state political campaigns. [344]

Over the past century, Virginia has transitioned politically from a predominantly rural, conservative state aligned with the [Solid South](/Solid_South) to a more urbanized, pluralistic, and politically moderate entity. This shift is attributed to increased voter enfranchisement and evolving demographics that have reshaped the electorate. Until the 1970s, Virginia operated as a racially segregated one-party state dominated by the [Byrd Organization](/Byrd_Organization). [345] This organization actively sought to counter the political influence of Northern Virginia, uphold [segregation](/Segregation_in_the_United_States), and successfully implemented measures that restricted voter registration, resulting in voter turnout consistently below ten percent between 1905 and 1948. [346] [347] The organization employed [malapportionment](/Malapportionment) to manipulate representation in the [General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly) and the U.S. Congress until court orders mandated the end of this practice following the 1964 [U.S. Supreme Court](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States) decision in [Davis v. Mann](/Davis_v._Mann) and the 1965 [Virginia Supreme Court](/Virginia_Supreme_Court) ruling in Wilkins v. Davis, respectively. [348]

The enforcement of federal civil rights legislation enacted in the mid-1960s was instrumental in dismantling the state's [Jim Crow laws](/Jim_Crow_laws), which had effectively [disenfranchised](/Disfranchisement) African Americans. [349] The [Voting Rights Act of 1965](/Voting_Rights_Act_of_1965) required Virginia, along with eight other states, to obtain federal approval for changes to voting laws, a preclearance requirement that was invalidated by the [2013 Supreme Court decision in *Shelby County v. Holder*](/Shelby_County_v._Holder). [350] In 2021, Virginia enacted the [Voting Rights Act of Virginia](/Voting_Rights_Act_of_Virginia), mandating preclearance from the [state Attorney General](/Attorney_General_of_Virginia) for local election modifications that could potentially lead to disenfranchisement, such as the closure or relocation of polling sites. [351] Although many Jim Crow-era provisions were removed from Virginia's 1971 constitution, the lifetime [ban on voting for felony convictions](/Felony_disenfranchisement_in_Virginia) remained in place. By 2016, an estimated twenty percent of African Americans in Virginia faced disenfranchisement due to prior felony convictions. [352] In that year, Governor [Terry McAuliffe](/Terry_McAuliffe) rescinded the lifetime ban and individually restored voting rights to over 200,000 former felons. [346] Virginia improved its ranking from the second most difficult state to vote in (2016) to the twelfth easiest (2020). [353]

While urban centers and expanding suburban areas, notably [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia), now constitute the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [base](/Base_(politics)), rural southern and western regions increasingly shifted their support to the [Republican Party](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) starting around 1970, influenced by the latter's "[Southern strategy](/Southern_strategy)". [354] [355] Nevertheless, Democratic support persists in union-influenced areas like [Roanoke](/Roanoke,_Virginia), university towns such as [Charlottesville](/Charlottesville,_Virginia) and [Blacksburg](/Blacksburg,_Virginia), and the southeastern [Black Belt Region](/Black_Belt_in_the_American_South). [356] African Americans represent the most consistent bloc of Democratic voters, [349] and educational attainment and gender have also emerged as significant indicators of political alignment, with a majority of women in Virginia supporting Democratic presidential candidates since 1980. [357] The influx of international immigrants and domestic migrants to Virginia has increased the proportion of eligible voters born outside the state from 44% in 1980 to 55% in 2019. [358]

#### State elections

