Although Virginia was considered a "[swing state](/Swing_state)" in the [2008 presidential election](/2008_United_States_presidential_election), [374] Virginia's thirteen [electoral votes](/Electoral_College_(United_States)) were carried by Democratic candidates in that election and the four subsequent presidential elections, suggesting a shift towards reliably Democratic presidential voting. Virginia was the only former Confederate state to vote for Democratic presidential candidates in the [2016](/2016_United_States_presidential_election_in_Virginia) and [2024](/2024_United_States_presidential_election_in_Virginia) elections. Previously, Virginia had voted for Republican presidential candidates in thirteen out of fourteen [presidential elections](/United_States_presidential_election) from 1952 to 2004, including ten consecutive elections from 1968 to 2004. [375] Virginia currently holds its presidential [open primary](/Open_primaries_in_the_United_States) on [Super Tuesday](/Super_Tuesday), concurrently with fourteen other states. [The most recent primary](/2024_Virginia_Republican_presidential_primary) was held on March 5, 2024. [376]

Virginia's two U.S. senators belong to [classes 1 and 2](/Classes_of_United_States_senators). Virginia has held [eleven U.S. House of Representatives seats](/United_States_congressional_delegations_from_Virginia) since 1993. The majority party in the delegation has shifted four times since then, often coinciding with "[wave elections](/Wave_elections_in_the_United_States)". Currently, six representatives are Democrats and five are Republicans. [377]

